1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
It's time to make your WordPress settings personalized to you and your site's needs.

2
00:00:06,480 --> 00:00:09,480
In this workshop, we're going to configure the general settings of your WordPress website,

3
00:00:11,760 --> 00:00:14,760
from blog titles to email address and even the site language.

4
00:00:16,040 --> 00:00:19,040
Let's start from the WordPress dashboard.

5
00:00:18,200 --> 00:00:21,200
I'm going to head over to settings on the left side.

6
00:00:22,080 --> 00:00:25,080
You're going to see the following options when you hover.

7
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:28,520
General, Writing, Reading, Discussion, Media, Permalinks, and Privacy.

8
00:00:32,160 --> 00:00:35,160
We'll cover all of these in separate workshops.

9
00:00:35,680 --> 00:00:38,680
First, to general settings.

10
00:00:38,600 --> 00:00:41,600
On the top, you'll see site title and tagline.

11
00:00:41,240 --> 00:00:44,240
You might have already set these up when you installed WordPress, but if you didn't or

12
00:00:45,760 --> 00:00:48,760
you want to rename them, this is where you can do that.

13
00:00:48,800 --> 00:00:51,800
I'm going to leave my name as My Food Blog, but I am going to change the tagline to "Roxie's

14
00:00:55,320 --> 00:00:58,320
Favorite Treats and Recipes."

15
00:00:57,920 --> 00:01:00,920
A pro tip here is to use descriptive names so that search engines can display your website

16
00:01:03,640 --> 00:01:06,640
properly.

17
00:01:05,080 --> 00:01:08,080
And now you can see that my site title and tagline are in the top left corner.

18
00:01:10,200 --> 00:01:13,200
Alright, let's move on to URL settings.

19
00:01:14,200 --> 00:01:17,200
This one is super important.

20
00:01:16,560 --> 00:01:19,560
The URL settings for your website, whether WordPress or site address, should be set up

21
00:01:21,920 --> 00:01:24,920
automatically with your install and are rarely changed in this settings area.

22
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:30,200
Honestly, changing the URL settings here can make your site inaccessible from the front

23
00:01:33,240 --> 00:01:36,240
or back end, and it would require access to the database to recover or repair these

24
00:01:38,520 --> 00:01:41,520
items.

25
00:01:39,520 --> 00:01:42,520
As a beginning user, the only time you'll probably use this is if you need to implement

26
00:01:44,720 --> 00:01:47,720
your SSL certificate.

27
00:01:46,800 --> 00:01:49,800
Okay, so on to email address.

28
00:01:49,920 --> 00:01:52,920
You can change your email here if you want to use a different address than what was used

29
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:57,400
when you set up WordPress.

30
00:01:56,280 --> 00:01:59,280
You'll get all admin emails and password reset emails to this address, so just make sure

31
00:02:02,240 --> 00:02:05,240
it's valid.

32
00:02:05,240 --> 00:02:08,240
Next we'll move on to Membership.

33
00:02:07,160 --> 00:02:10,160
With WordPress, you have the option to allow anyone to register for your site.

34
00:02:12,080 --> 00:02:15,080
If you select this option, you'll see that the new user default role is a Subscriber,

35
00:02:18,080 --> 00:02:21,080
so that new users have limited access to your dashboard.

36
00:02:21,800 --> 00:02:24,800
You can change this, however, I would recommend subscriber level.

37
00:02:26,080 --> 00:02:29,080
You can always update a user's role after they've registered to give them more access

38
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:34,000
and capabilities.

39
00:02:33,360 --> 00:02:36,360
I'm going to scroll down to the Site Language and select my preferred language from the drop-down

40
00:02:38,560 --> 00:02:41,560
list.

41
00:02:39,560 --> 00:02:42,560
For me, I'm going to confirm that it's English, and it's really important to make sure that

42
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:47,240
your language is selected because it'll help browsers and translation systems detect the

43
00:02:50,200 --> 00:02:53,200
website's preferred language.

44
00:02:52,200 --> 00:02:55,200
Okay, great.

45
00:02:53,600 --> 00:02:56,600
On to time zone.

46
00:02:55,320 --> 00:02:58,320
Select the city for your preferred time zone, or you could select the offset from Coordinated

47
00:03:00,680 --> 00:03:03,680
Universal Time, whichever one's easier for you.

48
00:03:03,920 --> 00:03:06,920
You'll see I went ahead and selected New York.

49
00:03:07,600 --> 00:03:10,600
Now I'm going to go on down to the date format.

50
00:03:10,760 --> 00:03:13,760
This date format will show on the front end of your website with any post metadata, like

51
00:03:16,280 --> 00:03:19,280
the author, date, time, that's with a new blog post.

52
00:03:21,400 --> 00:03:24,400
Now I can do the same thing for my time format, and I can even select different options and

53
00:03:26,680 --> 00:03:29,680
check them out in the preview.

54
00:03:29,520 --> 00:03:32,520
So if we head over to my food blog, you'll see that that date format shows up under a

55
00:03:33,920 --> 00:03:36,920
post, but date and time show up under a comment.

56
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:41,400
So with that in mind, make sure that you pick a format that looks good with your theme.

57
00:03:44,280 --> 00:03:47,280
Once I make my selection, I'll move on to the last segment, which is picking what day

58
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:51,400
I want my calendar widget to start.

59
00:03:50,560 --> 00:03:53,560
You'll see all of your options, but I'll keep it on Sunday.

60
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:57,400
When I'm done, I'll go ahead and save changes.

61
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:01,000
Great job personalizing those general settings for you and your site's needs.

